Quantum Gates and Qiskit

2023-07-20

Introduction to Quantum Gates

In quantum computing a quantum logic gate is a basic quantum circuit operating on a small number of qubits. A qubit is useless unless it is used to carry out a quantum calculation. The quantum calculations are achieved by performing a series of fundamental operations, known as quantum logic gates. They are the building blocks of quantum circuits similar to the classical logic gates in conventional digital circuits.

\[\newcommand{\ket}[1]{\left|{#1}\right\rangle}\]\[\newcommand{\bra}[1]{\left\langle{#1}\right|}\]\[\newcommand{\braket}[2]{\left\langle{#1}\middle|{#2}\right\rangle}\] The whole purpose of this site is to not only understand the theoretical aspect of quantum computing but also to understand the concepts quantum gates by programming it. Single Qubit Gates

There are some important \(2\times2\) matrices, which important to understand the basics of quantum gates. Just to work with them, lets start with the most simplest of all,

Indentity matrix or I-gate

The matrix is \(I = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}\).

Just as a revision, \(\ket{0} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\) and \(\ket{1} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\). Note that these are called computational bases and they obey Orthonormality.

Now, lets give \(\ket{0}\) through I-gate,

\(I\ket{0} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}= \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \ket{0}\)

Do try the same for \(\ket{1}\).

X-gate (Quantum Not)

Now lets simulate using qiskit.

## <qiskit.circuit.instructionset.InstructionSet object at 0x00000237906FB8E0>
